<DIV2 N="104" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>CHAP. CIV.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">Peregrine finding him&s;elf neglected by Sir Steady
Steerwell, expo&s;tulates with him in a letter; in
con&s;equence of which, he is forbid his hou&s;e,
$word$ his pen&s;ion, and incurs the reputation of a
$unatick.</HEAD>
<P>THIS pro&s;pect of &s;ucce&s;s, together with
his expectations from the mini&s;ter, whom
he did not neglect, helped to comfort him under
the rever&s;e of fortune which he had undergone,
and the uncertainty of the law-&s;uit, which he
&s;till maintained for the recovery of his ten thou|&s;and
pounds. The lawyers, indeed, continued
to drain his pocket of money, while they filled
his brain with un&s;ub&s;tantial hope; and he was
actually obliged to borrow money from his book|&s;eller,
on the &s;trength of the tran&s;lation, in order
to &s;atisfy the demands of tho&s;e ravenous harpies,
rather than lay the mi&s;anthrope under any diffi|culties,
or have recour&s;e to his friend Hatchway,
who lived at the garri&s;on, intirely ignorant of
his di&s;tre&s;s: and this was not at all alleviated by
the arrival of the Indiaman, in which he had
